04950nam a22006975i 9780823263950DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232639507 a10.1515/97808232639502doi  a(DE-B1597)555299  a(OCoLC)1178769225  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE457.5b.L735 2010eb 7aHIS0360502bisacsh04a973.70922221 aSymonds, Craig L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Lincoln Assassination :bCrime and Punishment Myth and MemoryA Lincoln Forum Book /cFrank J. Williams, Craig L. Symonds; Harold Holzer. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (256 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe North's Civil War00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Lincoln's Deathbed in Art and Memory -- t2. Abraham Lincoln's New York City Funeral -- t3. Not Everybody Mourned Lincoln's Death -- t4. Lincoln's Chief Avenger: Judge Advocate General Joseph Holt -- t5. The Lincoln Assassination in Law and Lore -- t6. Writing History in a Vacuum -- t7. ''Let the Stain of Innocent Blood Be Removed from the Land'' -- t8. Process versus Truth in the Case of the Lincoln Conspiracy -- t9. The Martyr and the Myth -- tList of Contributors -- tBoard of Advisors of the Lincoln Forum -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe assassination of President Abraham Lincoln remains one of the most prominent events in U.S. history. It continues to attract enormous and intense interest from scholars, writers, and armchair historians alike, ranging from painstaking new research to wild-eyed speculation. At the end of the Lincoln bicentennial year, and the onset of the Civil War sesquicentennial, the leading scholars of Lincoln and his murder offer in one volume their latest studies and arguments about the assassination, its aftermath, the extraordinary public reaction (which was more complex than has been previously believed), and the iconography that Lincoln's murder and deification inspired. Contributors also offer the most up-to-date accounts of the parallel legal event of the summer of 1865-the relentless pursuit, prosecution, and punishment of the conspirators. Everything from graphic tributes to religious sermons, to spontaneous outbursts on the streets of the nation's cities, to emotional mass-mourning at carefully organized funerals, as well as the imposition of military jurisprudence to try the conspirators, is examined in the light of fresh evidence and insightful analysis.The contributors are among the finest scholars who are studying Lincoln's assassination. All have earned well-deserved reputations for the quality of their research, their thoroughness, their originality, and their writing. In addition to the editors, contributors include Thomas R. Turner, Edward Steers Jr., Michael W. Kauffman, Thomas P. Lowry, Richard E. Sloan, Elizabeth D. Leonard, and Richard Nelson Current.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAssassinszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aConspiracieszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / Civil War Period (1850-1877).2bisacsh1 aHolzer, Harold, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWilliams, Frank J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823263950zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823263950423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823263950.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP